
The direction controls of language creation are currently not perfect.


ARTIST STATEMENT
I would say I decided to do this project because of my passion for worldbuilding. I really enjoy exploring different, unique worlds (especially by reading or playing as I 
Find those to be more immersive in their world building, some of my favorites are Warhammer(both 30k(Horus Heresy) and 40k), Bloodborne(as well as DS and ER), SCP containment breach, 
Dune, Witcher, D&D, among others.I love spending hours digging through lore, learning how these worlds fit together, like one of my guilty pleasures is watching hours of lore videos on 
YouTube, while I have free time or doing some easy work, and I also played and hosted some D&D. I enjoy my own amateur world building as well, so I wanted to create a tool that I or othersThose 
who want to enrich their worlds through languages or just want to explore languages in world building can use them to ideate, experiment, and quickly sketch out how a fictional language 
might look like how a fictional or fantasy creature might sound etc, without needing to fully master linguistics or spend months building a single conlang for a single idea.
This tool i more focused on rapid ideation rather than trying to design one perfect language. This project focuses on building a flexible language-generation workbench with a dark, sci-fi 
theme(cause I like that kind of theme) where you can tweak grammar settings, phonology, and writing system options, then instantly see sample words, sentences, and mini dictionaries. 
Itâ€™s part a toy, part a design tool, and part an excuse for me to dive deeper into the logistics of linguistics(languages) and world building.

Postmortem    (did use Grammarly for grammar correction and punctuation since I have it installed on the computer)
I think i bit off more than I could chew with some stuff, especially my original idea of having both a custom glyph generator that would generate glyphs for each of the  generated languages
As I started working on it and doing more research on word generation, sentence generation, conlanging(creating languages) etc. I realized how complicated things were
So I decided to only focus on teh language part of the thing rather than the glyph generation, so I ditched graphic glyph generation to just start using different pre-made letters and more
exotic alphabet characters integration rather than generation from zero. condensing my efforts helped a lot; however, the ui, style.css, and HTML parts took a very long time, especially the
HTML, since I'm not really good at HTML, even though I have like ideated by using ChatGPT, for templates/templates, it couldn't do what I wanted fully,  so I needed to tweak and fix stuff a 
lot, especially for moving parts like the sentence generator and  the dictionaries that hold my generated sentences, which I did, made some cool drop-down selection menus, and a good interface
And it became one of the parts I'm very proud of in the project, even though they are not perfect, they are very good(at least I think so). 

Then we have the main problem generation logicwhich I thought would be easy since I had so many rules right, it wasn't well, at least, it wasn't as good as I hoped it would be. 
It's a thousand times better than where it started, especially for generating sentences and words, and like follows all teh rules(I think). However, it still can't really generate an authentic feeling 
words, I mean it does generate words, but they don't look like teh ones we see in English, where they are very clearly structured, but that semi-random generation for you I spent a lot of time 
Looking for language generation logic and algorithms online; however, everything I found was not something I liked, where they were using outer APIs or logic so complex that i had no idea 
What it was doing even  after watching teh videos or reading about them, Markov chains, however, the easy way people used them was not really compatible with my other rule-based logic
I wanted to use as withy were just using outside libraries or APIs(markovify) to generate text from nothing, but I wanted to control how the text would be generated, but
I couldn't get them to work as they were a completely new topic for me, and were way more complex than I thought, and I probably shouldn't have wasted time trying to learn how to make them work 
the way I wanted (work together with my rule-based logic), which I realized was futile, so I realized I needed ot be to be content with this level of generation. It's not bad persay, but not the
Perfect one I wanted, still it works and looks relatively ok, so it's good, but as I said, generation was the hardest part to get right.




